How does the swarm know what to attack? In my head, I=E2=80=99m picturing d=
ifferent problems sending out pheromones to attract the swarm.=C2=A0
The intensity of the signal each problem sends at any given time is determi=
ned by a bunch of factors, including:=C2=A0
Total Addressable Market (TAM)
Economics=C2=A0
Visibility of the Opportunity
Technical Difficulty of the Problem
Market Structure / Barriers
Impact
Sexiness=C2=A0
How Solved the Problem Already Is
These combine and offset and balance each other, some factors attracting, s=
ome repelling. The ones with the highest net attractiveness attract the swa=
rm most strongly, but each also has its own unique scent which can attract =
certain kinds of people out of the great global swarm. Over time, as the sw=
arm attacks, the volume and types of people and capital each problem attrac=
ts evolves.=C2=A0
The swarm can descend upon whole industries =E2=80=93 like climate tech =E2=
=80=93 or specific opportunities =E2=80=93 like web3 UX. In either case, th=
e problems that are able to attract and hold the swarm=E2=80=99s attention =
for long enough will undoubtedly get fixed. This is one of the things that =
cynics get wrong =E2=80=93 the inability to see that the most obvious chall=
enges are like big flashing FIX ME signs to the swarm.=C2=A0
A bubble =E2=80=93 too many good solutions swarming the obvious problems =
=E2=80=93 is far more likely than the problem not getting solved!=C2=A0
Not to be gross, but a swarm=E2=80=99s success in solving a problem that it=
=E2=80=99s identified is as inevitable as those videos in which swarms of a=
nts eat food, like this:=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that each member of the swarm will succeed, or th=
at the swarm will behave rationally in the short-term. Often, the opposite =
is true: swarms are full of humans, and humans tend to get overexcited abou=
t the things that we get excited about, especially in groups.=C2=A0=C2=A0
It often goes something like this:=C2=A0
A few pioneering people get excited about solving a problem, either because=
 of its potential impact or just because of the technical challenge. Many f=
ail =E2=80=93 these problems are really hard! =E2=80=93 but a few succeed. =
Think Satoshi with peer-to-peer cash, an old unsolved problem, or Elon Musk=
 with reusable rockets.=C2=A0
When they solve the biggest technical or business model challenges, they al=
ter the pheromone balance, lowering the intensity of the repellants and inc=
reasing the intensity of the attractors. The swarm senses opportunity where=
 they didn=E2=80=99t before, and they fly at the problem=E2=80=A6 fast.=C2=
=A0
The space gets hyped. More people and dollars flood the space than it can r=
easonably handle because everyone is self-interested and sees similar oppor=
tunities. They don=E2=80=99t coordinate ahead of time, they swarm the marke=
t and compete.=C2=A0
While many companies fail and investors lose money, the swarm makes a meani=
ngful dent in the problem that it was trying to solve, in predictable and u=
npredictable ways.=C2=A0
