ped up and fade away, but eventually, the swarm smooths out problems until =
the sexiest, most challenging things are just boring, normal industries.=C2=
=A0
Everything that we take for granted today seemed nearly impossible once, be=
fore the swarm got to it.=C2=A0
Looking at Fast, climate, web3, and space, I think there are just three que=
stions that you need to ask to understand whether or not the swarm will fix=
 an industry=E2=80=99s shortcomings:=C2=A0
Are the problems physically solvable?=C2=A0
Is there a path to doing so profitably?
Will it matter if it=E2=80=99s solved?
That=E2=80=99s it. If any of the answers are no, the cynics are right. If t=
hey=E2=80=99re all yet, the optimists are.=C2=A0
In Fast=E2=80=99s case, the answers were yes, yes, no, so when the going go=
t rough, the swarm dissipated.=C2=A0
The space industry is the best at this way of thinking. Robert Zubrin=E2=80=
=99s The Case for Space [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkM1uhCAQgJ9m=
ua1Bflw9cGia9Ny0D2AQRiWLYABr7NN3Vg9NyJDMT76Zz-gCU0yHWmMu5BX6cqygAuzZQymQyJY=
h9c6qumEtl6IjVglbt7IlLvdjAli086qkDci6Dd4ZXVwM5wSlTJJZiUFSMMJaNphWiHFkTTPC8L=
D8IUdj7cXVm3UQDCj4gXTEAMSruZQ13_jbjX3g2_e90ov-jaEyccHEu85w_161gfsX_ES_vchXY=
vRumsv9M-bsBuddObDfrhjqhvO2lVzgAYpRxqiou5pJyrqKV7IWpoGxASG7jmp5E3SZWJW3IRdt=
ni8wSSrEMsTkwoTl56wX8GcB7-_xX7aAvB6CHjzYS025DJ-y-gkCJDRve13Qq6T8wZquk7jSqQL=
dSSY4rsQIkm3EqfAP_QN2QZO2 ] is 408 pages of taking seemingly impossibly fut=
uristic problems (like colonizing Mars, mining asteroids, or traveling to d=
istant stars), breaking them down to their physics and costs, and explainin=
g what will need to be true for solutions to be possible. Given the near-in=
finite stakes and potential impact, Zubrin treats even the hardest challeng=
es as a matter of when, not if.=C2=A0
While the laws of the economy aren=E2=80=99t as clean as the laws of physic=
s, I believe that solutions are equally inevitable as long as they answer =
=E2=80=9Cyes=E2=80=9D to all three of those questions above.=C2=A0
Whether via web3, VC, or good old fashioned free markets, the swarm is why =
I=E2=80=99m so optimistic about technology and humanity=E2=80=99s future. I=
t=E2=80=99s why I=E2=80=99m bullish on democracy and America, despite the d=
ivision and seemingly insurmountable challenges.=C2=A0
Yesterday, a16z Partner Katherine Boyle wrote an essay titled The Case for =
American Seriousness [ https://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxVkMFuhSAQRb_msdM=
ggsKCRZPm_YZBGZVUwcDYF_--0-eiacIwi5uZe-dMDmFJ-bJHKsh-vwGvA2yEV9kAETI7C-QheN=
t0QrdKGuat9I1WmoUyzBlgd2GzmE9gxzluYXIYUnxPcC4UW63peyHBKQ269VLqWfe8k1x5N8_Nr=
Mfb150-QJzAwjfkK0Vgm10Rj_JoPx7iSW90ObwglFKXcyzopq96SjsJBxWuUE2uQDWnXLkdMgWJ=
FWUP6SwRCq15Un1mFqzgQnDZmEYoLkzd1qqRUwdzB1IZw516SL4v4p8NyzYmHFMOcSH5ayWP7S3=
Q1QP1_YwBrwGiGzfwNxC8ub4RDQtEyMTbDw6JpuJtLzpjlNQ3ACKmhGwpkmDk7BNNxT_THzvskH=
Y ]. In it, she identifies a pervasive lack of seriousness as one of Americ=
a=E2=80=99s biggest meta-challenges. Instead of government intervention, sh=
e proposes entrepreneurship as the solution. In true Andreessen fashion, sh=
e proposes that Americans need to build:
Build housing for the middle class. Build schools for the kids who want to =
learn math. Build next-generation defense capabilities with young people wh=
o grew up coding. Build PCR tests so that a nasal swab stops the nation fro=
m closing businesses at the mere sight of Covid case increases. Build trade=
 schools. Encourage men and women to work with their hands again. Cut the r=
ed tape that stops us from building infrastructure fast. Build factories in=
 America. Build resiliency in the supply chain. Build work cultures that su=
pport mothers and fathers so they can have more children.
We do not need aging institutions to pave the way for American dynamism. Bu=
t we need American will.
The way I read it is that we need to do everything possible to let the swar=
m attack the biggest problems. Some are obvious and are already being swarm=
ed. Others need Elons to see opportunities where others see walls, Saccas t=
o appeal to the swarm=E2=80=99s greed for good, or web3 tools to align ince=
ntives and develop new models where current ones won=E2=80=99t quite fit.=
=C2=A0
Extreme optimism doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily lead to apathy. I=E2=80=99m ex=
tremely optimistic that the swarm will solve the world=E2=80=99s biggest ch=
allenges and move humanity forward, but the swarm is just the best efforts =
of billions of people solving the pieces of the problem that they can day a=
fter day until one problem fades and we move on to the next.
