100%; vertical-align: middle; width: 100%;"></a><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a;=
 font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">That doesn&#8217;t=
 mean that each member of the swarm will succeed, or that the swarm will be=
have rationally in the short-term. Often, the opposite is true: swarms are =
full of humans, and humans tend to get <em>over</em>excited about the thing=
s that we get excited about, <em>especially</em> in groups.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 1em 0;">It often goes something like this:&nbsp;</p><ul style=3D"margin-to=
p: 0;"><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; =
margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; f=
ont-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">A few pion=
eering people get excited about solving a problem, either because of its po=
tential <strong>impact</strong> or just because of the <strong>technical ch=
allenge</strong>. Many fail &#8211; these problems are really hard! &#8211;=
 but a few succeed. Think <strong>Satoshi with peer-to-peer cash</strong>, =
an old unsolved problem, or <strong>Elon Musk with reusable rockets</strong=
>.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-=
right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: =
#1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">=
When they solve the biggest technical or business model challenges, they <s=
trong>alter the pheromone balance</strong>, lowering the intensity of the r=
epellants and increasing the intensity of the attractors. The <strong>swarm=
 senses opportunity</strong> where they didn&#8217;t before, and they <stro=
ng>fly at the problem&#8230; fast</strong>.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8px; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-spe=
cial-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-hei=
ght: 26px; margin: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The space gets <strong>hyped</stro=
ng>. More people and dollars flood the space than it can reasonably handle =
because<strong> everyone is self-interested and sees similar opportunities<=
/strong>. They don&#8217;t coordinate ahead of time, they swarm the market =
and compete.&nbsp;</p></li><li style=3D"margin-bottom: 4px; margin-left: 8p=
x; margin-right: 0; margin-top: 4px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=
=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-b=
ottom: 0;">While <strong>many companies fail and investors lose money</stro=
ng>, the swarm makes a <strong>meaningful dent in the problem</strong> that=
 it was trying to solve, in predictable and unpredictable ways.&nbsp;</p></=
li></ul><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 1em 0;">This is where the bubbles come in, and why they&#8217;re a=
 good thing. As Byrne Hobart wrote in the excellent essay <em><a href=3D"ht=
tps://email.mg2.substack.com/c/eJxFkE2OhCAQRk_T7NoggsqCxWzmGoafUskoGCi645x-=
aF1MQiCpovLqe1YjLDGd6ogZyeea8DxABXjnDRAhkZIhTd6ptmdjJ7gkTnHXjmIkPk9zAti13xS=
mAuQoZvNWo4_hmqCUCbIq0RrG9cxlN1BnpR0Mn7tRaOGGkY8Du7m6OA_BgoIXpDMGIJtaEY_86L=
4e7LueuWBJ0Oi2_21s3GvlDdv2NLDqF7inKcZskJ-rz1gjPX0I8XUtU38SrxhljPJWtkxQJpuuE=
S23Pcw9cCEl1eLB6b6wJheTUdufD4MkFSKamHxYavtn1TtsV6Nmneq7l-DxnCDoyna3BrxtXmKm=
BQKkatlNGqtDQbuB9VIKPt6xqyfBeFdXYqSSXaxT4R_6B2AnjPM" rel=3D"" style=3D"colo=
r: #1a1a1a; text-decoration: underline;">Well-Behaved Bubbles Often Make Hi=
story</a></em>:&nbsp;</p><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #67bdf=
c; margin: 1em 0;"><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height=
: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0; margin-left: 1em;"><em><strong>Bubbles can be di=
rectly beneficial, or at least lead to positive spillover effects:</strong>=
 The telecom bubble in the &#8217;90s created cheap fiber, and when the wor=
ld was ready for YouTube, that fiber made it more viable. &nbsp;</em></p></=
blockquote><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 1em 0;">To stick with the swarm analogy, think of it like worke=
r bees dying to protect the queen. In the long arc of history, it doesn&#82=
17;t matter which company succeeded or how many sacrificed themselves in th=
e attempt, all that matters is that <strong>the swarm solved the problem</s=
trong>.</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 1em 0;">If that sounds familiar, it&#8217;s because the swarm e=
xplains the <strong>Gartner Hype Cycle</strong>. In fact, one way to think =
about how <strong>Hype Cycles</strong> happen is that exciting technologica=
l or business model breakthroughs send out signals to the swarm that a prob=
lem is now more solvable, and that there&#8217;s money to be made and impac=
t to be had for solving it.&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 1em 0;">The swarm attacks the problem=
 with more people, companies, dollars, and dreams for the new technology or=
 model until it becomes so competitive that it&#8217;s clear that not every=
one will win and that some of the early ideas were a little dumb. Then the =
weaker part of the swarm, the part attracted more by sexiness or TAM than t=
he technical challenge or impact, flies away while the passionate ones keep=
 building until they have commercially viable solutions that gain traction.=
&nbsp;</p><p style=3D"color: #1a1a1a; font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; m=
argin: 0 0 1em 0;">Their success attracts the part of the swarm attracted b=
y a different risk profile, the ones who want to work on more sure things, =
once the dust has settled. This is where an industry like B2B SaaS is today=
, on the Plateau of Productivity, or in what Carlota Perez calls the <stron=
g>Deployment Period</strong>. Things that once seemed impossible become mun=
dane. It&#8217;s pretty amazing.&nbsp;</p><div class=3D"captioned-image-con=
